Håkon Hapnes Strand, Data Scientist
Answered May 27, 2017 · Upvoted by
Justin Rising, MSE in CS, PhD in Statistics

I’m not so sure that SVMs aren’t popular, but it’s true that there are few use cases where an SVM would be the first choice in 2017.

In practical supervised learning, you could divide most of the problems into three general classes:

  • Clearly defined problems with small to intermediate datasets and a manageable number of features. Ensembling methods like boosted decision trees and random forests, sometimes combined with blending and stacking, are usually the best performing models on these problems.
  • Complex problems with big datasets and a huge number of features. This is the domain of deep learning. Various types neural networks are clearly outperforming other algorithms in this area.
  • Simple problems with special interpretability requirements. This is best handled by simple models like decision trees, linear regression, logistic regression and naive Bayes. SVMs are known for being hard to interpret.

An additional reason why SVMs might be falling out of fashion is that non-linear SVMs are expensive to train.

There are still problems where SVMs could be a logical choice. For instance, when there is enough domain expertise to construct meaningful kernels.

Ismail Elezi, Computer Science student
Answered May 4 · Upvoted by
Thia Kai Xin, M.S. Computer Science & Machine Learning, Georgia Institute of Technology

To be fair, they never were nowhere as good as the hype suggested. Even at their peak, you could have outperformed them with ensembles of trees (both boosting methods like Adaboost, or bagging methods like Random Forest). There was crazy hype over that because the purists liked the connections with function analysis and because they were the flagship of the so-called ‘kernel methods’ (despite that you could have got similar performances with kernelized logistic regression and kernelized least squares). However, I would say that the two main reasons why they are totally out of favor are:

  1. Data is hardly given as feature-vectors. In reality, more often than not, data might be images, videos, speech, text/language, music and so on. SVM by itself here is totally worthless and it needs some feature-extraction method in order to be well. The heavy lifting is done by that method (in images for example, SIFT-like algorithms) with SVM getting the output of that other method and then doing a classification there. That was working well 10 years ago, but with the post-2012 developments of deep learning, everything changed. The game changed from feature extraction then classification, to doing both feature extraction and classification at the same time. It works far far better, and deep neural nets not only made SVM quite irrelevant, but essentially killed entire fields like traditional computer vision, or traditional machine translation.
  2. But what if data is in feature-vector format? It happens at times. Well, people realized that it is very hard to beat Adaboost (in its extremely efficient xgboost library). And it is faster than kernelized SVM. To be fair, random forests work quite as well as gradient boosting, but still most people seem to prefer xgboost library (maybe because we don’t have something as efficient for random forests), just look at the winners of Kaggle competitions.

So, with the popularization of deep neural nets and gradient boosting methods, it has become hard to justify using SVM. There might still be cases for it where it might outperform other methods (you can say the same for Naive Bayes for example), but more often than not, it isn’t the best choice. It is a good algorithm that played a big part in the history of machine learning, but better algorithms have taken over.

Chomba Bupe, develops machine learning algorithms
Answered May 28, 2017 · Upvoted by
Arjoonn Sharma, Master's Computational Science & Machine Learning, IIITM- Kerala (2017)

Support vector machines (SVM), especially the kernel SVMs, are falling mostly out of favor because of the fact that they need ready real valued vectors as features. Given a complex problem like image recognition, how do you engineer the features in order to feed an SVM? It can be very cumbersome to do that.

The machine learning (ML) systems that are getting the most attention nowadays are end-to-end learning models. Specifically deep learning (DL) approaches are attractive because of that, a DL architecture is normally tasked to discover both the feature representations and the classifier function just from training examples alone.

However, you can actually use a linear SVM at the end of a deep convolutional neural network (convNet) and train them jointly using stochastic gradient descent (SGD) + backpropagation (backprop) algorithm.

Let me go a little deeper:

Assuming an architecture of the form:

input→→convNet→→SVM→→output

For simplicity let's use 1 linear SVM at the output, you can extend this easily to multiple outputs using 1 vs 1 or 1 vs all learning strategy. Here the linear SVM, for training purposes, is given a linear activation function just like in regression and the loss function is replaced by the hinge-loss defined by:

𝐿(𝑦̂ 𝑖,𝑦𝑖)=𝑚𝑎𝑥(0,1−𝑦𝑖𝑦̂ 𝑖)L(y^i,yi)=max(0,1−yiy^i)

where 𝑦𝑖∈[−1,1]yi∈[−1,1] and 𝑦̂ 𝑖y^i=actual output

SGD can also be replaced by stochastic sub-gradient descent instead since the hinge-loss is actually not differentiable. The whole architecture can thus be trained end-to-end that way, the error signal from the hinge-loss will guide the learning for both the convNet and SVM weights jointly. The hinge-loss results in the linear units directly connected to it learning maximum margin hyperplanes, which, in short, results in linear SVMs. In our example we have one linear unit hooked to the hinge-loss therefore after training we get a single linear SVM + a trained convNet for feature detection.

The convNet learns the hierarchical features while the SVM learns the final splitting hyperplane. After training is complete you can just apply a heaviside step function to the linear SVM output in order to get a binary output.

It is also possible to train the SVM alone on top of a pre-trained model like the VGG-16 network. The idea here is that you just need the right high-level features to feed to the SVM that is all. In most applications such as kernel SVMs the kernels just project low-level features to higher dimensional spaces but they don't capture the hierarchical nature of natural stimuli. That is another reason why kernel tricks are falling out of favor.

Linear SVMs at the end of a DL structure result in state-of-the-art performance. There is, after all, still potential in linear SVMs, probably it can help to explore a deep SVM architecture with appropriate non-linearity at each layer.

Hope this helps.

Shehroz Khan, ML Researcher, Postdoc @U of Toronto
Updated Sep 12, 2017

In summary, SVM is not a good approach

  • If your data is non-linear and you choose a linear kernel to model it.
  • If kernel and its parameters are not properly estimated/chosen.
  • The quadratic programming problem is computationally intensive and with increase in training data it can be very slow on normal machines.
  • SVM is mainly developed for binary classification problems. For handling multi-class problems, either you perform 1-against-all strategy or do other tricks like optimizing classes together, but i think that doesn’t perform any better.
  • Imbalanced data.

SVM is a classification method and its performance also depends on the type of features extracted. Keep in mind that number of features does not make SVM slow.

Some other good answers available on a similar question on this thread, For what kind of classification problems is SVM a bad approach?

More resources

  • Where do Support Vector Machines perform badly? • r/MachineLearning
  • How to explain poor classification performance of recall when using SVM?

Phillip Adkins, Data Scientist, Kaggle Master
Answered May 27, 2017

SVM can only be feasibly trained with a few 10’s of thousands of samples at most.

There’s a “sweet spot” for an RBF SVM.

  • 500-10k samples
  • 300–10k features
  • all features are expected to have similar information content / scale

That’s really the only problem; it’s good within that range of data attributes, but step outside that range and all of a sudden there’s going to be some algorithm that’s better, faster, and easier to use.

Linear SVMs are still good classifiers, usually better than a logistic regression.

Riccardo Belluzzo, M.Sc Telecommunications & Computer Science, University of Padua (2018)
Answered Sep 6

SVM can be attractive if applied in cases where you have small datasets with a reasonable limited number of features (human engineered in most of the cases). However, nowadays Machine Learning is used by a considerably amount of people that is not an expert in the field or, differently, don't have prior knowledge on how to process the dataset in order to extract effective features. End to end Deep Learning seems to be the solution for all this people and “classical”Machine Learning algorithms are (stupidly, IMO) not even considered. However, I believe that SVM still can be used effectively, especially in cases where the features used are coming from an automatic feature extractor module (e.g CNN) as proved by many recent publications.

Prabhash Kumarasinghe
Answered May 27, 2017

I think the main problem is that when u say w’x =0 to represent the hyperplane, x is assumed to have a good representation but in practice is hardly true. Even the kernel trick based solutions suffer from noisy dimensions and low quality features perhaps hand crafted. Deep learning trend has brought the importance of representation learning to the table, so now it seems to dominate. Further, deep neural nets seem to showcase what they have learnt from data, i.e. those low level to high level abstractions when weights are visualized. SVM shows no such artificial intelligence related qualities hence people may like the high accurate (e.g. MNIST), representation learning methods. But as per my understanding they lack mathematical properties as of svm. Pls correct me if I am wrong, im no expert.
